segments.text: July 30th, 1981, in Jacksonville, Texas, interviewing Major General Buckner as Terry Anderson.
And remember, we can take off and edit this tape, so just let's be as informal as possible.
This is an interview with Major General Buckner.
Today is the 30th of July, 1981.
This is Terry Anderson.
We want to start out by learning something about your background, sir.
Could you tell us where and when you were born?
I was born on January 11, 1919, in Cleburne, Texas.
Could you tell us about your parents?
My father was a city engineer, and my mother was the daughter of a house building contractor.
Did your father have a formal education for engineering, or did he just pick it up as a trade?
No, he was a graduate of the Texas A&M class in 1912.
Really?
There's a watch fob.
Oh, yes, it is.
A&M College of Texas, 1912.
That's great.
And he was very proud of the fact that he went all the way through at Texas A&M and he remained a private for four years.
He did.
But he worked his way through.
He scoped the furnishings at night and worked his way through the whole thing.
That's fantastic.
And then did he set up this company?
No, he had his own company and after he was city engineer in about 1921,
He decided to get into business for himself, and he started bidding highway jobs.
The first one he had was in Henderson, Texas.
And then from there, he went down there in the Austin, San Antonio area and worked on the highways down there.
We ended up in Austin.
Austin's where I started the school.
And from there we moved to Navasota.
It was very interesting because I started out in an experimental school there in Austin.
My sister was there as well.
She was a year ahead of me.
And at the end of the, I guess I was in the second grade,
I started the school at midterm when I was six years old, before I was six years old.
And it was very interesting because when I got to Navasota they put me back half a grade because I hadn't had enough math.
They put my sister forward a crate because this experimental school was so much more advanced.
I noticed last night when I was jogging through the area that there was a Buckner part of your family.
That's my uncle, yes.
Well, that part of it came later.
While we were at Navasota, my father was injured in an accident and crushed his leg.
hip and he was in an automobile accident and he had to go to the hospital in Houston and he asked his younger brother, Robert, to come over there and watch Eric do the job for him.
He came over there to help and Eric, while he went back,
Got in the cotton gin business and worked sawmill and a few other things.
And later on, my dad, after we moved from Navasota, we moved to Cleaver and he never moved from there again.
That's where we stayed until he died.
But R.C.
Robert, he invited him to come in partnership with him and he did.
And in about 1929 or 30,
And my dad liked to do work all over the state of Texas.
And he actually completed jobs in 250 of the 254 counties in the state of Texas.
And his brother lived here in, not here in Jacksonville, he actually lived in Sackle, which is down the road from here, not very far.
And they continued as Buckner Brothers for three or four years.
Robert R.C.
decided that he wanted to get married, and he didn't want to do all that traveling.
So they split up, and the company here was R.C.
Buckner until 1956, and then it became Buckner Construction Company.
And my father was John F. Buckner and later John F. Buckner's son.
He took all his sons in.
The business there, the war was over except for me.
Well, he offered me the opportunity.
I stayed in the Air Force.
And my youngest brother is still running that company, although the name of it now is Dan Buckner Incorporated in Cleveland.
In the meantime, R.C.
Buckner became Buckner Construction Company.
He became Buckner and Moore, and they split up.
He was a cousin of mine, by the way.
Right next door, M.G.
Moore.
His son, incidentally, went to M.G.
Moore.
And...
Robert R.C.
decided he wanted to get out of the business, and he knew that I was getting ready to retire from the service, and he offered me the opportunity to buy into the business.
And that's what I did in 1971.
Okay, let's go back and let's talk about your mother.
Tell me about her.
We haven't mentioned her.
Well, actually, she was born in Russ, Texas.
As I said, my grandfather was a house builder.
He built houses.
Then they went back to Cleveland.
And then she went to high school there, and she went to the University of Texas, and she taught school for a year or two.
I guess that's where they met, in Cleveland.
She never did go to college.
Oh, she went to the University of Texas.
Oh, I thought you said she went to high school, then she started teaching school.
No, she went to the University of Texas.
Okay, so both your parents then had degrees.
No, she didn't get a degree.
She got her teacher's certificate a couple of years.
Sure.
She taught school, and then after she got married, she raised five children.
What type of person was she?
Can you sort of describe her character?
Yes, she was very religious and very...
What religion?
Baptist.
Okay.
And my father was a very staunch Baptist, too.
He was chairman of the Lord of Deacons for a number of years, in charge of the building committee.
A staunch supporter.
Also a staunch supporter of Boy Scouts.
He was on the circle team of council.
And my mother was very active in...
the women's club activities that they had in the town.
She liked to garden and grow flowers.
She was a very sweet and understanding person.
There were a lot of people that took advantage of her for that reason.
She enjoyed other people.
Sounds like they were both involved in community activities.
Much so.
Except my father was on the road pretty deep.
He had jobs everywhere.
He traveled a lot.
He'd get up at 4 o'clock in the morning.
We wouldn't see him until evening or maybe only on Sunday.
He was always there on Sunday.
I missed out.
Can you tell me, can you sort of describe your type of person, the character of your father?
Well, I'd have to say that he was, if you ever called anybody straight arrow, that's what he was.
His word was bond, and he wouldn't intentionally beat anybody out of anyone.
He was very, very meticulous about it, about human relationships.
He had a great strength of character.
He was a strong-willed man.
Yes, very strong-willed man.
He didn't drink, he didn't smoke, he didn't swear.
He was a straight arrow.
Was he tough?
Or was he understanding?
I imagine some people would call him tough, but he did have a very good sense of understanding, a feeling of understanding.
It sounds like religion was important in your upbringing.
Is that true?
That's true.
Sunday school and church every Sunday.
Usually twice on Sunday.
Church twice on Sunday.
In the morning and in the evening too.
And sometimes on Wednesday evening.
Who is the authority in the household?
My father.
All of them.
My mother was left with a lot of things to do because he was gone for sure.
And you had five, there were five children in the family, so you had four siblings.
Yeah.
How'd you get along with them?
Tell me, what happened to them?
I mean, did they also become leaders like you did?
Well, my sister married a dentist.
She lives in Cleveland.
She was the oldest.
My next older brother was in the Marines during the war.
He was a tank battalion commander.
And the next brother was in the Marines.
He was a pilot for the B-25s.
And the youngest one was in the Navy.
He just got in as the war ended, I think.
He was just a sailor on a ship.
My sister graduated from Baylor.
And my next oldest brother graduated from the University of Texas, and the other two graduated from Texas A&M after the war.
So it started before, but then ended up after finishing up.
If religion was a strong influence, why didn't all the children go to bail?
My dad had one prerequisite.
He sent us to school.
Everybody had to have at least two years of military time.
I don't know that any of the children were quite as religious as your parents.
We do go to church.
What happened to your brothers?
Are they still in the engineering business?
No, the youngest one is the only one still alive.
The other two both contacted me.
some kind of fungus or something to deal with asthma out in Southwest Pacific during World War II, and they had trouble breathing.
And the next to the youngest, Arthur, had a worse case, and he was allergic to his own infection, and he moved to

Well, he came back after the war and he started working and he had a job out in the Alpine, which is a higher level and he seemed to do better, but it didn't get better, enough better, so he moved to Arizona.
Went to work.
He got a graduate degree from the University of Arizona.
He worked for the state for a while, and then he got out on his own selling water systems.
He was selling and installing water systems.
He's also an engineer?
Yes, he was a civil engineer graduate.
But he died...
The year before last.
And my next oldest brother, Erwin.
He died when he was 45 years old in 1960.
He had a cardiac arrest.
He was a business administration lady.
He was in the business with my father.
Three brothers were there for a while, and finally the one brother had left in Arizona, and the other two were in, and were my father.
Now, for...
people in your period, your generation.
It was not that typical for young people to go to college, but not only did your parents both attend college, but all the kids went to college.
Wow.
Why was that?
We were all
motivated and oriented in that direction.
Your parents continually told you that someday you're going to college?
There was never any other future in mind except going to college.
My father
that put himself through college, and he was that way from the time he was born.
He knew he wanted to go to college, and he did it.
And that's the same, I guess he,
motivated us in the same direction.
Now you've had a very successful career, rising to gentleship, and I was wondering in what ways do you think that your parents are responsible for that?
Well, I guess my father was the most responsible because he insisted on the military training.
I went to John Tarleton.
I got indoctrinated into the military there, so I decided that I wanted to make a career.
It was a very forceful
Major Bender, who was a colonel during World War II that killed a beach in Normandy.
He was a character.
was a great influence on my children.
I liked the life that he led, and I liked him.
I liked his family, and I enjoyed the military.
He inspired them.
Yes, he did.
As a matter of fact, he talked me into taking CMTC in 1938.
And I was there on the book of formation as soon as I was 21.
And there he introduced me to recent graduates from West Point.
And they taught me how to go into West Point.
Ostensibly, Lieutenant Meyer, who was an Army football player, found out that I was an all-Congress football player in Virginia College.
He was going to get me an appointment in West Point, Pennsylvania.
At the meantime, he told me to go for my own challenge, which I did.
I took the entrance exam.
I made the highest grade of the people who were taking it.
He had two appointments, I believe, one to the Naval Academy and one to the Military Academy.
So I chose to go to the Military Academy.
That's where I really wanted to go.
Why did you decide on the Army and then the Air Force instead of the Navy?
Well, I was going to the Army because I wanted to be in the infantry.
At that time, I didn't know anything about the Air Force.
The connection I had with the Air Force, I had marched with the Army.
Well, we had a crack platoon that marched in the Battle of Flowers Parade in San Antonio.
We got to go out to, I believe it was either Brooks or Kelly Field, and we got to crawl over some airplanes, and that was my first association with airplanes.
I saw that they did a fly-by there, too.
Were you pretty impressed?
I was very impressed, but I didn't know whether I had the proclivity that it took me an 80-year-old.
I mean, I really, as I look back now, I wasn't that enthusiastic about it.
I thought it was great, but I was in the emphasis.
Let's go back to your education, though.
You were telling me about Austin.
What about your junior high and your high school?
Well, we moved to, we moved to Cuba from, uh, Minnesota to Cleveland.
And, uh, we were there, you know, I think I was in the
I suppose I was in the second grade.
And I went to the third and the fourth and the fifth grade to a elementary school.
And then we moved to another area of the city.
And I went to what was called the junior high, because it had the elementary grades plus the junior high all at once, just across the street.
I got a couple blocks from the high school.
I finished junior high and went right into high school.
What were your favorite subjects?
I suppose, man.
Did you excel at that?
Yes, I made new friends.
After I found out that you had to behave, after being switched a few times to sit on the steps during recess and those types of disciplines, I learned that
My dad promised me a bicycle if I'd get on the honor roll three months in a row.
And the main thing I had to overcome was to be into Portland, which I did.
And I got a bicycle.
You said that you were a footballer?
Yes, I started football when I was in Jan Long's elementary school in fifth grade.
I played in the sixth grade and I was on the junior high team.
I played four years in high school.
What position?
Guard.
Guard?
Must have been a tiger, you know.
You don't look like you're big enough for a guard.
Well, in those days, they had smaller people.
I weighed more than a pound.
In high school, I weighed 170 pounds.
I was heavier than 175 pounds.
My goodness.
That's why I played guitar all the time.
Were you in other activities in school?
Yes.
Oh, I was in a music memory contest.
I was in a play.
We didn't have too many activities.
We were so poor, we didn't even have an annual.
Right.
Would you consider yourself a leader in high school, and I was interested when?
When generals start assuming leadership roles, when do you think you did?
Was it in high school?
Yes, it was in high school.
I was captain of the football team and captain of the basketball team.
Did you like that role?
Yes.
Then I was co-captain in junior college.
Would you consider yourself popular in high school?
Well, I don't think, I don't remember anything.
I was too shy, and I didn't date much.
I was popular with the boys, but that way with the girls I wasn't particularly popular.
Did you have a lot of friends?
Yes, I did.
Why do you think that they picked you for the captain of these two teams?
Well, it's hard to say.
But it wasn't because I was very articulate, because I wasn't.
I never was an articulate person of equations.
I guess they looked to me because I was able to make good grades and I knew all the plays and I helped them in the game.
Now this, of course, is right during the Great Depression.
I was wondering at the Depression,
a pathetic economic situation on the country in the mid-1930s had any impact on your upbringing and your family?
Well, nobody had any money.
Everybody was in the same boat, but no one had fun.
Every once in a while, I guess, I'd get a nickel to get an ice cream cone.
I was a small kid.
When I was a small kid, I came out here to East Texas and worked on my grandfather's farm.
And I got interested in farming, and I decided I wanted
a cow.
I started milking cows and my father bought a cow when I was about to
third or fourth grade.
Later on he added another one, so I met with gals twice a day until I got out of high school.
My brother has cursed me ever since.
He goes, I went to my next older brother after I left, and after he left I went to the next one, and after he left I came to the last one, and the last one sort of cried him up.
And he was happy it did dry up.
Did the depression have any effect on your father's business?
Oh yeah.
I think he went broke.
At least he ran out of money.
He had to move in with my grandmother in Cleveland.
But he started all over again.
He kept on going.
So if he was broke, in other words, he was unemployed for a while?
No, he wasn't employed.
He just didn't have a job.
Oh, you mean he didn't, no one, in other words, no one hired his construction services?
Well, it wasn't a question of that.
When you run out of money and you have to sell all of your equipment, well, he had to sell all of his equipment after the job was over.
He got injured.
He got all this trouble.
I don't know how mad all people was financially, but I know that we didn't have any money.
Did you have enough food on the table?
Oh yes, we raised a lot of food.
And of course I was milking the cow.
things got better.
He started making money, I suppose.
The construction business would have a bad job, especially back then when you only had one job at a time.
You had to move your mules and everything with you, but he had to sell all his mules and all his equipment.
And it may have been a good thing because they started mechanizing everything after that, but we never had mules again.
When you graduated from high school, had you already made up your mind what you wanted to be?
Did you have firm ideas?
I thought I wanted to be a mechanical engineer.
When I left high school, that's what I took at Tarleton and A&M.
At A&M, I decided I wanted to get a degree in mechanical and civil engineering, and then go to MIT and get a master's in mechanical engineering.
That was my goal.
I thought it would change my mind at Tarleton, and I wanted to go there.
Why?
Why MIT?
Well, that was just the reputation they had.
In my mind, it was in my mind as a good place to go to get a master's degree.
It's my dad's name, and it must be someone to be a part of his thing.
But that was my, that was what I had outlined when I said I would go.
During the Depression, did
Your father support the New Deal and Franklin Roosevelt?
Do you remember?
I haven't the slightest idea.
Was he in any way political?
Not that I know of.
Did he vote?
Oh, yes, he voted.
Who did he usually vote, Democrat or Republican, or conservative or liberal?
I don't know.
Democrats.
I know, but I mean, did he vote for liberal Democrats or ones that supported?
I don't think we had any.
in Texas, they may have been.
But the ones that we had on a national level, I know, the guy that appointed me to the military, he was an old-time conservative.
Are there local legislators, state legislators?
I don't know too much about politics.
When did you start paying attention to politics?
After I got the right to vote, let's see, up until 19, I don't know what year, I don't remember what year it was, criminals and regular army people could not vote for the state of Texas.
I was a regular army .
And when you finally did get the franchise, who did, what party, or what, did you vote, liberal, moderate, or conservative, independent?
Conservative.
Mostly Republican.
And are you a member of a political party now, or are you just?
I call myself independent.
I support a lot of Republicans, but I support a lot of Democrats, too.
We have a state senator here, Peyton McKnight, I strongly support.
He's a Democrat.
I support Governor Reagan, President Reagan, and I support him.
I'm supporting all these programs too.
Now, why'd you decide on Tarleton?
Why'd you immediately go up to Tarleton instead of going to A&M?
Well, I was thinking about the two years of military.
And also, I thought I had a better chance to play football there than I did at that time.
And you made the $10,000.
Yes.
I was not given a scholarship then.
I was just a walk-on.
But I went over early and started to practice.
Finally got some of the big boys hurt.
It allowed me to have a chance to show what I could do.
The coach of the team was Chuck Saunders, the guard from S.E.U.
He helped me a lot.
He was really good.
He taught me a lot.
And then you stayed there for one year, is that not correct?
Two years.
Did you go to A&M for one year, or did you go directly from?
I went two years to Tarleton, then I went to A&M, and while I was at A&M, I took the entrance.
So you went to A&M for one year, which would have been your junior year?
After your two years at Tarleton.
Why did you decide on A&M, and why didn't you try to transfer into MIT or some other engineering school?
Well, I'd already picked A&M.
I was going to A&M.
Why?
Well, I had a lot of friends that were going there, too, and I had already decided that's where I wanted to go.
I was going to MIT for Masters.
Okay.
Can you describe the accommodations when you arrived?
Where'd you stay at, Andrew?
I stayed in Goodwin Hall in a triple-decker bunk.
A triple-decker?
I had two of my friends from Tarleton there with me, and we were junior fish, which is not a very
savory position and enjoy at that time.
It may be better now, but it was horrible then.
You had a heavy course load and you did everything a freshman did.
Sure.
What about employment?
Did you work while you were at A&M?
No.
How were you supported?
How could you afford to pay for it?
My father
My father sent me.
So by that time you had your father's business had been covered enough so he- Oh yeah.
It had been covered in early 30's.
Now, what corps outfit were you assigned?
I was an A company infantry.
Did you enjoy being in the corps?
Yes, I did.
What were some of the things that you enjoyed about it?
Well, I enjoyed the friendship and the association with the individuals.
The spirit permeated the whole mountain.
We thought we were the best.
Nobody could tell the difference.
Were there any things that you disliked about being in the court?
Well, I didn't like being a freshman.
In other words, you didn't like servicing the, uh, ugliness of the nightly seniors, some of them who were younger than I was.
Sure.
What about hazing?
I had all I wanted.
but I had had a year of it at Tarleton.
Can you compare the hazing of Ann and Tarleton?
About the same, except we didn't have the...
There wasn't as much of the room cleaning.
Was there as much as we didn't have?
We only had one dormitory there, and it was a brand new one.
I went in when I was a freshman.
I lived in a rooming house.
I was the only one who lived in that rooming house.
Then when I went into the dormitory, everything was worked out from there.
By the time we got to the upperclassmen, we had a few things going.
Everybody had to be in the military there.
Sure.
No question about it.
Did they use the board as much at Tarleton as they did at A&M?
A physical hazing.
Well, they used the Sam Brown belt both places.
I don't know if you're familiar with the Sam Brown belt.
No, I'm not.
Tell me about the belt.
and they had holes in it and it'll make it really tear you up in the rear, turn you purple, blue, orange, green, any color you wanted.
Let's compare the type of hazing at A&M and West Point.
It was very similar, except there was no physical hazing.
They weren't allowed to touch you at West Point.
They did not beat you.
That's not to say there couldn't be rifle exercises until you passed out.
And did they do that?
Oh, yeah.
Pushing the piece and things like that?
Yeah.
Plenty of similarity.
The toughest warning at West Point was the needles that you had to sit at attention.
Keep your eyes on the blood, not look up.
Keep your posture in a very stiff, erect position.
It's not very...
I think they've cut that out now, so they allow me to be made to sit up.
So, in other words, the hazing at A&M and at West Point were similar in the mental hazing.
Same types of demands?
Well, there are even more demands that West Palm would say, insofar as the mental is concerned, because you haven't memorized a bunch of stories.
They can call on you at any time to recite them, and if you need more of them, they can set up.
They might allow you a few seconds, a few minutes to eat, and that would be all.
and at A&M the difference was that we had the physical and there was no physical hazing at West Point.
What was your opinion of hazing both at A&M and then at West Point?
I thought it had a place and a lot of it was good.
And what was it?
Tell me about the place that it is.
Well, they had what they called clothing formations, and you'd have to run upstairs and change your clothes and get back and do the last one when you got in trouble.
And this is at Westmoreland?
Yeah.
And it taught you to change clothes in a hurry and get them right, because if you went down there wrong, you had to go back and it ended up with lots of problems.
And I really had no problem with it because I'd been through what I'd had to talk and what I'd had to answer.
And I had no trouble memorizing the stuff.
I had no trouble in the formations I'd ever had to be in, the violent stuff.
Some of them I had to go through because we had troubles.
What do you mean violent?
Well...
The...

more stressful situations maybe violent is too strong a word more stressful situations because what they were doing is trying to create a stress situation which occurs in all military under stress and try to put you in a stress situation and get you so that you know how to react under a stress situation and i think that's good it's not overdone and it also
teach you attention to detail, and teach you to take care of your parents, and if they found a spot on you, boy, you'd get on for that, or something like that.
It's a good mental training.
What about the, in other words, you're saying that hazing teaches you discipline.
That's right.
What about, this question, in what way do you think being in the Corps, both at Tarleton and A&M, helped you at West Point and later in your career?
Well, I knew, I would say this, that I knew close order drill as well as the ones that were trying to teach it to me up there.
It was not better because I had more of it than they had.
Actually, I didn't have any, and also I didn't have any new subjects there for the first three years except for French, which I hadn't had before.
So it was relatively easy for me, and I was coaching my classmates who were having problems.
So in other words, you had a good preparation here in Texas before?
Yes, sir.
before you went to West Point.
I said, well, I think it's a waste of time.
They don't do that anymore.
They give people credit, and they take other courses.
They have a curriculum now that's not so high-balanced.
Everybody had to take the same thing.
That's what it was when I went there.
Everybody had to take the same thing.
In other words, when you went to West Point, the credits that you took at A&M didn't transfer?
It meant nothing.
No kidding.
Absolutely nothing.
Well, were you a little irritated by that?
Well, not really.
It didn't make any difference.
It didn't take any more.
I was going to have to be there.
I don't think I read the interview.
What about the quality of military training at A&M versus military training at West Point?
Well, insofar as, as I said, close artillery and things like that, A&M is better.
But in the other subjects, your military training at A&M didn't go as deep or cover as many subjects because you covered only the infantry.
I was in the infantry.
Up there we covered the whole gamut.
We studied every one of the services, each individual service.
I didn't go to the field training at A&M.
I went to the CMTC, which is, I guess, similar.
We had field training in the summer, which was a lot more realistic training .
What about the engineering courses that you took?
As I said, the first three years, I didn't have engineering courses, and it's almost the same.
Which one did you enjoy more?
Well, you've got to put that in perspective.
I enjoyed them both.
But did you enjoy the one you finished most?
Sure.
There was no question about that.
The year you enjoy most is the senior year, and I never had a senior year.
Oh, that's true.
At A&M, I had a good year, but it left some things to be desired in terms of freedom, relationships.
Oh, would you explain?
Well, if you're a junior fish, you're doing nothing.
It's not a great deal of plagiarism.
You get nothing for a year.
Well, it really wasn't nothing.
You're sort of a second-class citizen.
Now, people at A&M, many of the former students think that there's something special or unique about A&M.
Sometimes they mention spirit.
They just say it's more than an institution.
Do you think that?
Yes, I agree with that.
You agree with that?
Yeah.
It's the same at West Point.
It's the same at West Point.
Yes, it is.
Okay.
Now, there's a spree decor, of course, at West Point.
